ValueType.Equals() defined [here](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/System.Private.CoreLib/src/System/ValueType.cs) should compare bits of objects if the compared type doesn't contain any reference type. But it seems that it always uses reflection to check equality. (Corect behavior is described [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/dotnet/api/system.valuetype.equals).)

For example folowing code prints True:

```csharp
public class Program
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        TestStruct f, s;
        f.variable = 0.0f;
        s.variable = -0.0f;
	
        Console.WriteLine(f.Equals(s)); //True -> binary check was not used
    }
}

public struct TestStruct
{
    public float variable;
}
 ```

This is probably bug because same code on .Net 4.7.2 prints False. If this is intended feature than there should not be line 42 and 43 in file [ValueType.cs](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/System.Private.CoreLib/src/System/ValueType.cs)

